3140	\begin{lemma}[Finite affine cover with quasi-compact overlaps]
3141	  \label{lem:finite_affine_cover_qcqs}
3142	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.exists_finite_affineCover_inter_isQuasiCompact}
3143	  \uses{}
3144	  A quasi-compact scheme \(X\) admits a \emph{finite} affine open cover
3145	  \(\mathcal{U} : X = U_1 \cup \dots \cup U_t\). If moreover \(X\) is
3146	  quasi-separated, then each pairwise intersection \(U_{ij} = U_i \cap U_j\) is
3147	  quasi-compact; and if \(X\) is separated, each \(U_{ij}\) is in fact affine.
3148	  \begin{proof}
3149	    \uses{}
3150	    The affine opens form a basis, so \(X\) is covered by affine opens; quasi-compactness
3151	    extracts a finite subcover \(U_1, \dots, U_t\) (by Mathlib's affine cover and the
3152	    finite-subcover property of a quasi-compact space). Quasi-separatedness says the
3153	    intersection of two quasi-compact opens is quasi-compact, so each \(U_{ij}\) is
3154	    quasi-compact. When \(X\) is separated the diagonal is a closed immersion, whence
3155	    the intersection of two affine opens is affine (Mathlib, for separated schemes).
3156	  \end{proof}
3157	\end{lemma}

